			<h4><a id="comment_link_36399864" name="comment_link_36399864" href="//it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=2227792&amp;cid=36399864" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(36399864)" >The irony of spam is...</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_36399864" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 36399864); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Paul+Fernhout">Paul Fernhout</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Paul+Fernhout">(109597)</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_36399864"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_36399864"><p>The irony of spam is it results from having a tool of abundance (email, useful for building a better world, whether more of a gift economy or better designs or in other ways) in the hands of a few people obsessed with making money (ration units) in the current scarcity-based economic paradigm that emphasizes one-for-one exchange and privatizing profits while socializing costs. So, spammers poison the email system trying to get a bit of resources for themselves, and while doing so make it harder for the rest<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_36399864">

